        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>April 1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Dyer</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>The plants arrived all save &amp; will be very useful.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> They are kinds which, as I formerly ascertained, move much quicker to than from the light, but I suspect do not change their centre of rotation (i.e. do not bend towards light), &amp; this is a curious point, which I am anxious to ascertain.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> The Anoda will also be very useful, &amp; you have sent me a prodigious supply of Trifolium seeds—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>Many thanks | Ever yours sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.2 much] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.3 (i.e. … light)] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11950.xml">letter to W. T. Thiselton-Dyer, 24 March 1879</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The plants requested by CD were listed in the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11950.xml">letter to W. T. Thiselton-Dyer, 24 March 1879</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">In <hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi>, pp. 451–2, CD discussed plants in which the speed of rotation was faster when moving towards the light than when moving away from it, attributing this to a vestige of heliotropism.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD had requested seeds of <hi rend="italic">Anoda wrightii</hi>, probably in order to observe the movement of the cotyledons (<ref target="./DCP-LETT-11950.xml">letter to W. T. Thiselton-Dyer, 24 March 1879</ref>; <hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi>, pp. 302–3). <hi rend="italic">Anoda wrightii</hi> (a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Anoda lanceolata</hi>) is a species of mallow;  <hi rend="italic">Trifolium</hi> is the genus of clover.</note>
        </div>   
       
